The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, June 10, 2004 				 Finance firms shine in rating sweepstakes
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 																								Mumbai, June 9: None of the financial services firms have earned a default-grade rating since 1999, says a Crisil report which cites robust fundamentals, strong parentage and sweeping consolidation as the key reasons. At the heart of the improvement in their credit-worthiness has been the NBFC shakeout in the second half of the 90s. 																								While a number of these companies have assumed a new role, some smaller players have gone away. The direct impact of the consolidation in the NBFC sector has been the strengthening of the business models of existing NBFCs, the agency said.																								D. Thyagarajan, director of financial sector ratings, said a sharper focus on retail lending has also helped.
